"type": "note",
"subtopic": "1. Introduction",
"content": "Blood is a fluid connective tissue that flows in a closed system of blood vessels. The heart acts as a muscular pump that keeps blood moving. Blood vessels include arteries (carry blood away from the heart), veins…\n\n• Contains blood plasma only is associated with Contains blood plasma with blood platelets and proteins.\n• Contains blood plasma only — Antigen on RBCs: Contains blood plasma with blood platelets and proteins.\n• Red blood cells (RBCs) — contain haemoglobin and transport oxygen.\n• White blood cells (WBCs) — fight infection and provide immunity.",
"explanation": "Definitions:\n• Contains blood plasma only — associated with Contains blood plasma with blood platelets and proteins\n• Blood — a fluid connective tissue that flows in a closed system of blood vessels\n• Capillaries — the finest blood vessels that interconnect arteries and veins; exchange of water, nutrients, wastes and respiratory gases occurs through capillaries\n• Oxygen — absorbed into the blood for circulation\n\nAlso know:\n• Platelets — help in blood clotting at wound sites.\n• Plasma — the liquid part (about 55% of blood); carries nutrients, hormones, waste and proteins.\n• Arteries carry blood away from the heart; veins carry blood towards the heart.\n• Lymph is the fluid which flows in the lymph vessels.",
"source": "icse",
"examTip": "Read this section, then tap Practice linked MCQs before moving on.",
