"topicId": "bio-ch9",
"type": "note",
"subtopic": "21. Honeybees — Apiculture",
"content": "The insects which provide us honey are known as honeybees. The honeybees keep honey in their nest, which is known as the beehive. A beehive has small compartments — combs. The shape and size of the comb depends on the…\n\n• All activities such as laying of eggs, rearing of the larvae and pupae are done in the combs.\n• Three types of adults are present in the beehive — queen, drone (male) and workers.\n• There is only one queen in the whole of the colony.\n• Drones are smaller in size than the queen and their function is to fertilise the queen.\n• Their function is to look after the queen and also keep the colony clean.",
"explanation": "Definitions:\n• Flowers — associated with Rose, jasmine, gladiolus, marigold, larkspur, balsam\n\nAlso know:\n• Honeybees are mainly used to extract honey and beeswax.\n• Honey is a rich source of carbohydrates.\n• Beeswax is used in making candles, cosmetics, etc.\n• Honey is produced by honeybees from the nectar of flowers.",
"source": "icse",
